vidia-shall-inherit-the-earth ) we discussed Netflix=E2=80=99s burgeoning a=
d business and whether Nvidia is set to dominate because of AI. On Ditherin=
g ( https://dithering.fm/ ) we discussed the court case below, but our disc=
ussion was more about Apple=E2=80=99s complicated relationship with develop=
ers. You can add both podcasts to your podcast player using the links at th=
e bottom of this email.

On to the update:

Apple, Epic, and the Court of Appeals
-------------------------------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-wins-fede=
ral-appeal-in-app-store-case-brought-by-fortnite-maker-epic-games-ea8c5df4 =
) :

A federal appeals court sided with Apple Inc. and upheld a 2021 ruling that=
 mostly supported the company=E2=80=99s App Store policies against an antit=
rust challenge by Fortnite maker Epic Games Inc. A panel of three judges on=
 the Ninth U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Monday sided with a federal jud=
ge=E2=80=99s ruling that rejected all but one of Epic=E2=80=99s claims and =
declared that Apple doesn=E2=80=99t have monopolistic control over mobile g=
ame transactions.

=E2=80=9CThere is a lively and important debate about the role played in ou=
r economy and democracy by online transaction platforms with market power,=
=E2=80=9D the ruling concluded. =E2=80=9COur job as a federal Court of Appe=
als, however, is not to resolve that debate=E2=80=94nor could we even attem=
pt to do so. Instead, in this decision, we faithfully applied existing prec=
edent to the facts as the parties developed them below. =E2=80=9C

This is a pretty fun excerpt in that it manages to quote a line in the deci=
sion that refutes the lead: Apple does have market power, but the ruling af=
firmed that Apple=E2=80=99s exercise of that market power was pro-competiti=
ve according to federal law. California law is another question.

Apple=E2=80=99s Federal Victory
-----------------------

I find this decision ( https://www.pacermonitor.com/view/WETSUQA/Epic_Games=
_Inc_v_Apple_Inc__09cae-21-16506__0215.1.pdf ) much more digestible than th=
e District Court=E2=80=99s, which is just as well as this will be controlli=
ng precedent for the 9th Circuit going forward; that latter point is good n=
ews for Apple as any federal antitrust case would likely be filed in the 9t=
h Circuit (which is to say that a federal antitrust case has probably becom=
e much less likely, but not impossible). Given the precedent-making nature =
of this ruling I thought it would be useful to summarize the 91-page decisi=
on:

*Market Definition:* The Appeals Court agreed with the District Court=E2=80=
=99s market definition of =E2=80=9Cmobile-game transactions=E2=80=9D, altho=
ugh it disagreed with some ways in which the District Court dismissed Epic=
=E2=80=99s proposed market definitions of the =E2=80=9CiOS app distribution=
 market=E2=80=9D and a separate =E2=80=9CiOS in-app payment solution market=
=E2=80=9D.

The important takeaway is the one I predicted in App Store Arguments ( http=
s://stratechery.com/2021/app-store-arguments/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUz=
I1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJh=
dWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8=
vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29tLzIwMjEvYXBwLXN0b3JlLWFyZ3VtZW50cy8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTY4NT=
AyMjkxMywiaWF0IjoxNjgyNDMwOTEzLCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb=
3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpy=
ZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjo=
iYWNjZXNzIn0.D5R8wCVSSzl35A6n9kEW1mziglF568TYBHX5l5Je-WoaZyA3RQc2ovqDmogBZM=
EUgjvYxqu69G-nAtTi3BZUVORvFP5WtfANzIXLm-5yCuVV_FO5LTF0HdTZiTai9e6TRVEH63PgR=
TtUYVlnbSE9wFRk4CxfKygSIcYpsUI6vcNnV2INxvhjCdui6udmSa9f9j3N5T7-9FHyzU-I4W_R=
sm1Kx6xuxVLHa_E8R4K0oQ87r1mj4AoK6xs2Pdw3l4CIVEUYi3nV5uz9VYJJVY7rx-gLBrD2NnI=
JGriU-uLOYgtp1pUk0zxri8TzQ_9fXav3ca2Y2xyONrvNZp1cQVV1jA ) :

First, while it is possible to define the App Store for iPhones as a distin=
ct aftermarket (see Kodak v. Image Technical Services), appellate courts ha=
ve significantly narrowed that decision to limit its application to situati=
ons where the company selling the product that leads to an aftermarket is o=
nly barred from changing the rules after-the-fact to foreclose competition =
in the aftermarket; if the rules foreclosing competition are consistent, ho=
wever, then there is no harm, because customers know what they are getting =
into. In the case of the iPhone, this means that Apple can control the mark=
et for iPhone apps, because customers already know that Apple controls the =
App market; if they don=E2=80=99t like it they can buy a different phone. T=
his is why Apple spent time in the trial establishing that its control of t=
he App Store was in fact a selling point of the iPhone, and a reason why cu=
stomers chose to enter iOS=E2=80=99s more restrictive ecosystem.

From the decision, agreeing with the District Court=E2=80=99s dismissal of =
Epic=E2=80=99s market definition:

In sum, to establish a single-brand aftermarket, a plaintiff must show: (1)=
 the challenged aftermarket restrictions are =E2=80=9Cnot generally known=
=E2=80=9D when consumers make their foremarket purchase; (2) =E2=80=9Csigni=
ficant=E2=80=9D information costs prevent accurate life-cycle pricing; (3) =
=E2=80=9Csignificant=E2=80=9D monetary or non-monetary switching costs exis=
t; and (4) general market-definition principles regarding cross-elasticity =
of demand do not undermine the proposed single-brand market.

This point about customer knowledge of Apple=E2=80=99s rules is a critical =
one that will be repeated below.

*Sherman Act Section 1: Unreasonable Restraint:* Here the Appeals Court sai=
d the District Court was wrong to not consider the Developer Program Licens=
e Agreement (DPLA) a contract covered by Section 1; given that the DPLA is =
a pre-requisite for distributing iPhone apps developers didn=E2=80=99t have=
 much choice to agree to it. This is a good reversal.

Next, the Appeals Court agreed with the District Court that Apple=E2=80=99s=
 App Store policies imposed substantial anticompetitive effects. However, t=
he Appeals Court agreed with the District Court that those anticompetitive =
effects were balanced by the pro-competitive effects of Apple improving dev=
ice security and user privacy, and to a partial extent Apple=E2=80=99s abil=
ity to collect its IP licensing fee. Of these two reasons it is the former =
that is more important: just as above it turns on the idea that consumers k=
now about, value, and make choices based on Apple=E2=80=99s App Store rules=
, which means that Apple=E2=80=99s anti-competitive actions in isolation ar=
e ultimately pro-competitive in the broader market.

Because use of the App Store requires an iOS device, there are two ways of =
increasing App Store output: (1) increasing the total number of iOS device =
users, and (2) increasing the average number of downloads and in-app purcha=
ses made by iOS device users. Below, the district court found that a large =
portion of consumers factored security and privacy into their decision to p=
urchase an iOS device =E2=80=94 increasing total iOS device users. It also =
found that Apple=E2=80=99s security- and privacy-related restrictions =E2=
=80=9Cprovide[] a safe and trusted user experience on iOS, which encourages=
 both users and developers to transact freely=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94increasing t=
he per-user average number of app transactions.

I do think that this is true; I have maintained all along that the App Stor=
e has increased the size of the addressable market for developers. Still, e=
ven if this is true Epic could have proposed =E2=80=9CSubstantially Less Re=
strictive Means=E2=80=9D for Apple to deliver the same benefits while decre=
asing the anticompetitive effects; the Appeals Court agreed with the Distri=
ct Court that Epic failed to do so.

*Sherman Act Section 1: Tying:* While the Appeals Court denied Epic=E2=80=
=99s market definition, here it disagreed with the District Court =E2=80=94=
 and agreed with Epic =E2=80=94 that the App Store and In-app Purchase are =
distinct products , and that they are tied. However, the Appeals Court, bas=
ed on the Microsoft antitrust case precedent, held that tying in software m=
arkets is not per se illegal, given the rapidly changing nature of those ma=
rkets and concerns about making first-mover advantages =E2=80=94 i.e. innov=
ation =E2=80=94 illegal. That means a rule of reason analysis is appropriat=
e, which Apple wins for the exact same reasons as above. I do agree with th=
is section in its totality.

*Sherman Act Section 2: Monopoly Maintenance:* This section wasn=E2=80=99t =
really contested by Epic, as they put all of their eggs in the market defin=
ition basket (and a single-brand market would be an obvious monopoly); the =
Appeals Court defaults to agreement with the District Court here, and added=
 that even if Apple were a monopoly, the same arguments as above would stan=
d.

Epic=E2=80=99s California Win
---------------------

This is the part of the case that will have the most far-reaching effects, =
and why I=E2=80=99m not sure it=E2=80=99s correct to rule this decision as =
an Apple victory. To recall, while the District Court found in favor of App=
le as far as federal antitrust law is concerned, it did rule in favor of Ep=
ic when it came to California=E2=80=99s Unfair Competition Law (UCL); speci=
fically, it found that Apple=E2=80=99s anti-steering provision, which preve=
nt apps from linking to a website that includes alternative means of paymen=
t, was a violation of the UCL=E2=80=99s prohibition on =E2=80=9Cunfair cond=
uct.=E2=80=9D At the time ( https://stratechery.com/2021/the-apple-v-epic-d=
ecision/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3N=
wb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vb=
mxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29tLzIwMjEvdGhlLWFw=
cGxlLXYtZXBpYy1kZWNpc2lvbi8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTY4NTAyMjkxMywiaWF0IjoxNjgyNDMwOTE=
zLCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3=
BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQiLCJzd=
WIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.RhrtXmUqXIsncVgS=
FrEiriSXea97A5LIuLDuNB97fOneKN64wFTFHW4xfrYK2rZowDzqeZEHvvYdyrnCaqpfwb2YTar=
-B5nmpFqxjIHkgExq-_03nO_Gm-gtw8qMfb9Yh7Z-VggOcUQSdT8ztwPO0lB3vfGJzaLu2TiIdb=
QoS5tgb2XLyoDUujEKM5Ix-4sw_hpIxzcrxzYwwh1nYFqIae_zt8zG8lr5HpETUrPJOEIrBTVKf=
Q1UdT5GHQO_S0XnU8lY5-FH-BblQ5PiQjbMpxvd8lv2s6-bj0nuObdmmzi51zReN3-8BgUjzUIY=
iOzp8mKNnSj5LI2Ys9x8DNIsvw ) I thought this might not hold up under appeal =
given Epic barely addressed the point in its case, and the fact the Distric=
t Court handed down a nationwide prohibition on the practice.

In fact, it did hold up under appeal, and that means there are meaningful c=
hanges coming to the App Store. First, the Appeals Court agreed that the st=
andard for a UCL violation was different than for a federal antitrust viola=
tion, and that Apple violated that standard. Second, the Appeals Court rule=
d that given every app developer could potentially link to the Epic Games S=
tore that every developer was affected by Apple=E2=80=99s prohibition, not =
just Epic.

This is a very big deal! It certainly seems to me that, barring an en banc =
appeal and corresponding injunction, and beyond that the Supreme Court, tha=
t Apple=E2=80=99s anti-steering provisions are now illegal throughout the U=
nited States. Moreover, this illegality extends to all apps =E2=80=94 both =
games and everything else.

I think that distinction is important because it shows how Apple went wrong=
: for years I have argued that Apple should force games to use in-app purch=
ase while letting other apps link to the web; most of the company=E2=80=99s=
 App Store revenue comes from games, and games are the most problematic as =
far as potential abuse is concerned. This would relieve pressure on the com=
pany while preserving most of its revenue and, as a nice side effect, accom=
modate apps like e-book readers or streaming services who literally can=E2=
=80=99t operate under Apple=E2=80=99s current rules (and thus must trust cu=
stomers to find their own way to the web).

Now, though, it appears that Apple will have to allow all apps to link to t=
he web, including games. Yes, it will be harder to convert on the web, rela=
tive to in-app purchase, but you can be sure that developers will be eager =
to see how well it works. What is not clear, though, is whether or not Appl=
e is permitted to pursue its IP-licensing fees: will Apple seek to audit ap=
ps with links to their website to collect 27% of their revenue? This isn=E2=
=80=99t addressed in either the District or Appeals Court rulings.

On this morning=E2=80=99s Dithering ( https://dithering.fm/ ) episode I fra=
med this ruling as a clear Apple win; the fact that the anti-steering injun=
ction survived, though, has me changing my tune a bit. This is a pretty mea=
ningful shift to the App Store, especially if Apple is not allowed to pursu=
e its share of revenue that is generated on said websites (stay tuned!).

What is worth noting, though, is that Apple would have been in such better =
shape had it made this concession previously: it might have avoided this in=
junction completely (again, Epic barely mentioned it; this sprang almost en=
tirely from the judge=E2=80=99s shock at testimony about the anti-steering =
provision=E2=80=99s existence), it could have foreclosed federal App Store =
laws (which this case makes clear are the only way to change the App Store)=
, and most importantly, it would have provided a better user experience for=
 customers of apps like Kindle, Netflix, or even Stratechery (I certainly w=
as not going to build an app as long as this restriction was in place).

Indeed, the best thing Apple could do now is lean into this decision: go ah=
ead, declare victory, and then frame a removal of the anti-steering provisi=
on as a developer-friendly change at June=E2=80=99s WWDC. Apple is going to=
 be forced to make changes to the App Store to some extent; it is losing ti=
me to do so on its own terms =E2=80=94 and to head-off legislative changes =
that will make the biggest difference to its bottom line.

